   WPP Stock Falls
                                                                                                       

   WPP Group's shares tumbled sharply Friday, with its
American depositary receipts falling $1.75 to $19.375 in
national over-the-counter trading.
   Analysts attributed the drop partly to fallout from
problems at FKB Group, a similarly structured British
advertising and communications company, whose shares Friday
were halted from trading in London because of a credit
crunch. FKB, like WPP, bought a number of companies on an
earn-out basis, in which it makes payments based on earnings
over a number of years. FKB apparently is facing problems
meeting the payments. Julie Mackee, chief financial officer
of the company's U.S. operations, said FKB is "in the process
of negotiating a refinancing package with our bankers" and
trading "won't resume until we're in a position to announce a
detailed refinancing proposal."
   WPP is far larger than FKB, and analysts said it isn't
facing troubles like those at FKB. But because of
well-publicized problems caused by softness in the ad
business, particularly at Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co., "anything in
that sector that implies bad news really seems to affect
everyone else" disproportionately, Ms. Mackee noted. WPP
executives couldn't be reached for comment.
